titleStmt.title: HuTime Ontology to Represent Uncertain Time Intervals

sourceDesc.bibl: HuTime Ontology to Represent Uncertain Time Intervals, Ontologies for Linked Data in the Humanities, 2019) prepared for the Ontologies for Linked Dara in the Humanities Workshop at the DH2019 conference in Utrecht, sponsored by the Alliance for the Digital Humanities Linked Open Data Special Interest Group, and organized by Kim Martin and Susan Brown with committee members Johanna Drucker, Ryan Shaw, Joseph T. Tennis, and Jasmine Drudge-Willson….

abstract.p: The way that data about the Humanities' central research area, the human record, is stored, retrieved, and visualized, shapes what digital-resource users can know about the past, and how they can use what they learn to inform the future. The Humanities are on the cusp of transformation as cultural data moves from quantities that can be comprehended at a human-scale (in, for example, digital monograph form, or in a single small database) to quantities that produce new knowledge through macro-visualization and computational inferencing – all provided that the academic community and beyond can develop pathways to continue to expand expertise in harnessing semantic web data. The Digital Humanities community and the GLAM sector have produced beautiful curated TEI, much of which serves individual projects well, but which has not been used beyond its home project. This paper reports on the attempts (following where others have tread) to create linked data from TEI resources. The process of creating linked data is far from straight forward, since TEI is by nature hierarchical, taking its meaning from the deep nesting of elements. Furthermore, the meaning the TEI elements are not always well-represented in existing ontologies. In addition to sharing our work to date, we are especially keen to solicit feedback from peers on the balance between granularity and generality in the representation of TEI-based information about people, places, time, and cultural production as linked data.

title.title: HuTime Ontology to Represent Uncertain Time Intervals

bibl.author: Tatsuki Sekino (International Research Center for Japanese Studies)

div.head: Introduction
div.p: Names of a period such as historical eras are used to represent time. However, the boundaries of these periods are often ambiguous and not fixed at specific values. For example, the “Renaissance” did not suddenly begin or end on one day. Therefore, temporal range of the “Renaissance” is usually represented as a time interval with the beginning and end ranges (e.g., from the 14th to 16th centuries). OWL-Time (W3C 2017) is widely used as a standard ontology for representing temporal information, but it is difficult to apply to ambiguously dated periods. This is because OWL-Time was designed under the assumption that all time-interval boundaries are fixed at specific values.

Sekino (2019, 2020) proposed a logic about uncertain time intervals that can be applied to represent and compare ambiguous periods. This article discusses HuTime Ontology for use in describing uncertain time intervals based on Sekino’s logic. A definition of HuTime Ontology is available on the Internet (http://resource.hutime.org/ontology/).

div.head: Uncertain Time Intervals
div.p: We define a time interval that the boundaries are represented as range, to be an uncertain time interval (Figure 1). The boundaries of uncertain time intervals are typically not fixed at specific values. When the beginning and end ranges are separate (Figure 1A), the intervening temporal range (reliable time interval) shows a range that is certainly included within the uncertain time interval. The whole temporal range including the ranges of all possible boundaries (possible time interval) shows an overall range that may be included in the uncertain time interval. In other words, the outside ranges of the possible time interval are never included in the uncertain time interval. Consequently, an uncertain time interval is determined according to four time instants: (i.e., the beginning range is set between the beginning points of the possible and reliable time intervals, while the end range is set between the end points of the reliable and possible time intervals).

figure.figDesc: Figure 1. The concept of uncertain time intervals (Sekino 2019 and 2020). Since the beginning and end ranges of (A) are separated, the reliable time interval exists in (A). While, the reliable time interval does not exist in (B), where the beginning and end ranges overlap. The duration of the beginning and end ranges of (C) are zero. This means that (C) is in the same situation as (D), which is represented as a time:ProperInterval of OWL-Time.
Figure 2. Structure of HuTime Ontology and its relation to OWL-Time.

div.head: HuTime Ontology
div.p: HuTime Ontology was designed based on OWL-Time. Uncertain time intervals are represented as a class of hutime:UncertainTimeInterval in HuTime Ontology. To maintain compatibility with OWL-Time, the hutime:UncertainTimeInterval is defined as a subclass of the time:Interval, which includes all types of time intervals in OWL-Time (Figure 2). The hutime:UncertainTimeInterval is also defined as a super class of time:ProperInterval, which represents actual time intervals in OWL-Time. This is because time:ProperInterval can be regarded as an uncertain time interval with durations of the beginning and end ranges that are set at zero (Figure 1C and D).
An uncertain time interval is described according to the four following properties:

table.head: An uncertain time interval is described according to the four following properties:

row.cell: the beginning point of the beginning range
the end point of the beginning range
the beginning point of the end range
the end point of the end range

div.p: These property names originated from the uncertain time interval concept (Figure 1). The range of these properties is time:TemporalEntity. Therefore, any temporal entities according to OWL-Time are available (e.g., the beginning range of Term1 in Figure 3). Julian dates (JD) are also available to describe uncertain time intervals, as follows:

row.cell: JD of the beginning point of the beginning range
JD of the end point of the beginning range
JD of the beginning point of the end range
JD of the end point of the end range

div.p: JD is total day counts beginning at noon on January 1, 4713 BCE (Dershowitz & Reingold 2007). This makes it easy to compare temporal data. The ranges of these properties are described by numerical values of a double type (e.g., the end point of Term1 in Figure 3). JD values can also be described according to time:TimePosition of OWL-Time and are available to specify the four values in an uncertain time interval through usual properties of hutime:hasPossibleBeginning and other three. However, these JD properties are added to HuTime Ontology to efficiently obtain JD values, which are useful for calculation. The beginning and end points of uncertain time intervals are represented as ranges (Figure 1). The following two properties are thus defined in HuTime Ontology to specify these ranges:

The class of range for these properties is hutime:UncertainTimeInterval. This means that an uncertain time interval is recursively available to describe another uncertain time interval (e.g., Term4 in Figure 3). Time intervals of time:ProperInterval are also available for use in describing uncertain time intervals (e.g., the end point of Term4 in Figure 3). This is because time:ProperInterval is a subclass of hutime:UncertainTimeInterval.

div.head: Applying HuTime Calendar Linked Open Data
div.p: HuTime Calendar Linked Open Data (LOD) (http://datetime.hutime.org/) provides information about calendar periods (e.g., dates, months, years, and eras) as resources for semantic web technology (Sekino 2017). Although other services provide information about calendar periods, the HuTime Calendar LOD is unique in its provision of information about periods from various calendars (e.g., the Japanese Calendar) and ability to interpret character strings representing calendar periods. The HuTime Calendar LOD was also designed according to HuTime Ontology. Thus, calendar periods provided by the service are defined as hutime:UncertainTimeInterval. These calendar periods are therefore available for use in describing uncertain time intervals. In Term2 of Figure 3, the beginning and end ranges of an uncertain time interval are directly specified using calendar month resources (i.e., from the Japanese Calendar) other than those from the Gregorian Calendar.

All calendar periods provided by the HuTime Calendar LOD are linked to JD values through the properties of hutime:hasPossibleJdBeginning and the other three. It is thus easy to obtain the JD values of the related boundaries when an uncertain time interval is described by these calendar periods. Such uncertain time intervals that are linked to JD values can efficiently be used for analysis or retrieval.

div.head: Discussion
div.p: HuTime Ontology is useful for describing uncertain time interval. Since Sekino (2019 and 2020) proposed procedures for making comparisons and retrievals between uncertain time intervals, the data described using HuTime Ontology are also available for any analyses based on these procedures. Most existing data according to OWL-Time are also available for the analysis frameworks used in HuTime Ontology. This is because HuTime Ontology and OWL-Time contain compatible platforms.

HuTime Ontology contains a function by which uncertain time intervals are recursively used to describe other uncertain time intervals. For example, released LOD representing the “Renaissance” and “Industrial Revolution” can be used to create an interval spanning both periods that is defined as the “Early Modern Period.” This newly defined period can also be released as LOD for any user to apply as metadata or conduct retrievals. This definition of a period consisting of other periods also connotes a different meaning from those that are only defined by dates. That is, the definition includes the original meaning of the period. Increased amounts of LOD concerning such time periods may promote the growth of a large-scale semantic network designed to connect temporal information.
